										<content:encoded><![CDATA[<!DOCTYPE html PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD HTML 4.0 Transitional//EN" "http://www.w3.org/TR/REC-html40/loose.dtd">
<html><body><ul class="wp-block-list">
<li>Visit the site here <a href="https://victoria-hertel-site.vercel.app/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">victoria-hertel-site.vercel.app</a></li>



<li>Take a look at the <a href="https://github.com/vanghoa/victoria-hertel-site" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">github repository</a>.</li>
</ul>



<p><strong>1. Website Concept</strong><br><strong><br></strong>Victoria is an artist, whose <em>installations combine sensor technology, trace and motion to construct distilled sensory encounters that heighten our awareness of the material network we inhabit, </em>as she stated on her bio.<br><br>I really like the idea of interconnectedness present in each of her works. the idea of people entering the space, connecting with a work, and having an experience with it became really important to Victoria. Within each connection, lie the traces left by the connectings and the connecteds.</p>



<p>Then I looked into The Wayback Machine, a digital archive of the World Wide Web founded by the Internet Archive. Simply put, it allows the user to go &ldquo;back in time&rdquo; to see how websites looked in the past.</p>



<figure class="wp-block-image size-large" style="--width:1024; --height:658;"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" width="1024" height="658" src="/wp-content/uploads/2024/09/image-10-1-1024x658.png" alt="" class="wp-image-492" srcset="/wp-content/uploads/2024/09/image-10-1-1024x658.png 1024w, /wp-content/uploads/2024/09/image-10-1-300x193.png 300w, /wp-content/uploads/2024/09/image-10-1-768x494.png 768w, /wp-content/uploads/2024/09/image-10-1-1536x987.png 1536w, /wp-content/uploads/2024/09/image-10-1-2048x1316.png 2048w" sizes="(max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px" fetchpriority="high"></figure>



<figure class="wp-block-image size-large" style="--width:1024; --height:658;"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" width="1024" height="658" src="/wp-content/uploads/2024/09/image-11-1-1024x658.png" alt="" class="wp-image-491" srcset="/wp-content/uploads/2024/09/image-11-1-1024x658.png 1024w, /wp-content/uploads/2024/09/image-11-1-300x193.png 300w, /wp-content/uploads/2024/09/image-11-1-768x494.png 768w, /wp-content/uploads/2024/09/image-11-1-1536x987.png 1536w, /wp-content/uploads/2024/09/image-11-1-2048x1316.png 2048w" sizes="(max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px" fetchpriority="high"></figure>



<figure class="wp-block-image size-large" style="--width:1024; --height:658;"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" width="1024" height="658" src="" alt="" class="wp-image-430" srcset="" sizes="(max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px" data-src="/wp-content/uploads/2024/09/image-79-1024x658.png" data-srcset="/wp-content/uploads/2024/09/image-79-1024x658.png 1024w, /wp-content/uploads/2024/09/image-79-300x193.png 300w, /wp-content/uploads/2024/09/image-79-768x494.png 768w, /wp-content/uploads/2024/09/image-79-1536x987.png 1536w, /wp-content/uploads/2024/09/image-79-2048x1316.png 2048w"></figure>



<p>That idea resonated so much with what I felt about traces on the net. I wanted to make something like that, something that reflects the site growth/development on the site itself, showing the traces of the owner/developer behind this site.</p>



<p>Then I wondered how I could actually make this happen (obviously I don&rsquo;t expect myself to build something like wayback machine from scratch). I needed to find a way to pull it off with my web development skills (&amp; time budget). Fortunately, Git commit history came to mind. Git, a version control system for tracking file changes, was a perfect fit for what I wanted. GitHub should expose APIs that allow me to extract this data and visualise it in whatever way I want!</p>



<figure class="wp-block-image size-large span2md" style="--width:1024; --height:516;"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" width="1024" height="516" src="" alt="" class="wp-image-431" srcset="" sizes="(max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px" data-src="/wp-content/uploads/2024/09/image-80-1024x516.png" data-srcset="/wp-content/uploads/2024/09/image-80-1024x516.png 1024w, /wp-content/uploads/2024/09/image-80-300x151.png 300w, /wp-content/uploads/2024/09/image-80-768x387.png 768w, /wp-content/uploads/2024/09/image-80-1536x775.png 1536w, /wp-content/uploads/2024/09/image-80-2048x1033.png 2048w"></figure>



<p><strong>2. Visual Concept</strong><br><strong><br></strong>We had a hard time deciding on this aspect, but finally settled on using visual cues from polaroids. They fit perfectly with the concept of capturing and storing website snapshots. Additionally, from a personal perspective, Victoria mentioned that she always took polaroids at each of her shows and exhibitions.</p>



<figure class="wp-block-image size-large span2" style="--width:1024; --height:614;"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" width="1024" height="614" src="" alt="" class="wp-image-432" srcset="" sizes="(max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px" data-src="/wp-content/uploads/2024/09/image-81-1024x614.png" data-srcset="/wp-content/uploads/2024/09/image-81-1024x614.png 1024w, /wp-content/uploads/2024/09/image-81-300x180.png 300w, /wp-content/uploads/2024/09/image-81-768x461.png 768w, /wp-content/uploads/2024/09/image-81-1536x922.png 1536w, /wp-content/uploads/2024/09/image-81.png 2000w"></figure>



<p class="row2">Observing the polaroids, I wanted to elevate this polaroid concept to another level. I specifically took notice of the developing process of polaroids&hellip;<br><br>&hellip;It came to me that in digital space, there is a similar concept &ndash; the Progressive Loading method of JPEG! The internet nowadays is so fast that we often fail to notice all these artifacts operating in the background.</p>



<figure class="wp-block-image size-full span2" style="--width:797; --height:441;"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" width="797" height="441" src="" alt="" class="wp-image-433" srcset="" sizes="(max-width: 797px) 100vw, 797px" data-src="/wp-content/uploads/2024/09/image-82.png" data-srcset="/wp-content/uploads/2024/09/image-82.png 797w, /wp-content/uploads/2024/09/image-82-300x166.png 300w, /wp-content/uploads/2024/09/image-82-768x425.png 768w"></figure>



<figure class="wp-block-image size-full span2" style="--width:600; --height:339;"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" width="600" height="339" src="" alt="" class="wp-image-434" srcset="" sizes="(max-width: 600px) 100vw, 600px" data-src="/wp-content/uploads/2024/09/image-83.png" data-srcset="/wp-content/uploads/2024/09/image-83.png 600w, /wp-content/uploads/2024/09/image-83-300x170.png 300w"></figure>



<p><strong>3. Final site</strong><br><strong><br></strong>Here is the JPEG progressive loading in action! Following by the git commit history/website snapshot history visualiser!</p>



<figure class="wp-block-embed is-type-video is-provider-vimeo wp-block-embed-vimeo span2 row2"><div class="wp-block-embed__wrapper">
<div style="--width:960; --height:760;"><img decoding="async" style="--twidth:960; --theight:760;" alt="thumbnail" src="" data-src="https://i.vimeocdn.com/video/1903931292-2896254d63b5408f2529bfba4ab787334f39d15e014e5d3511629098b788f8cd-d_960" data-srcset="" srcset=""><iframe title="Victoria Hertel site - JPEG Progressive Polaroid" src="" frameborder="0" allow="autoplay; fullscreen; picture-in-picture; clipboard-write" data-src="https://player.vimeo.com/video/988297118?dnt=1&amp;app_id=122963"></iframe></div>
</div></figure>



<figure class="wp-block-embed is-type-video is-provider-vimeo wp-block-embed-vimeo span2 row2"><div class="wp-block-embed__wrapper">
<div style="--width:960; --height:760;"><img decoding="async" style="--twidth:960; --theight:760;" alt="thumbnail" src="" data-src="https://i.vimeocdn.com/video/1903929650-89f99383d8bc0a0511e54b6d5da0256ed2883c275deb2af36940c10d0b42b3c1-d_960" data-srcset="" srcset=""><iframe title="Victoria Hertel site - History Timeline View" src="" frameborder="0" allow="autoplay; fullscreen; picture-in-picture; clipboard-write" data-src="https://player.vimeo.com/video/988297150?dnt=1&amp;app_id=122963"></iframe></div>
